item.title: What is a Network
item.description:
A Network is two or more connected computers that can share resources such as data, applications, machines, Internet connections. They communicate using Binary.
LAN
Local Area Network is physically connected devices that are in close proximity to each other. Normally connected to via a hub or a switch physically.
Try to put LAN's into Work-groups such as Marketing or Sales.
This is for the purpose of easier Administration.
Logical Vs. Physical
Logical is when some device is noting logically where a device connects to another instead of actually being connected physically.
Its like If I wrote on a piece of paper where my Home is but I my not be physically at my home yet. That is what Routers are for.

About Name Convention Host, Workstation, and Client are all used interchangeably by most people to refer to the same thing so be sure to be careful technically.

Workstation:
- Power PC with more than one CPU
- Resources are available to others on the network Note Workstations are not as powerful as a Server and they are not a client computer or personal computer but could be technically.
Server:
Very Powerful Computers that are "at the service" to the network and generally do one specific task but can do many tasks if you wanted to.
They Run on whats called a network operating system.
They give resources to a ton of client machines
File Server: Stores and Deletes Files
Mail Server: Email Functions
Print Server: Manages Printers
Web Server: Utilities HTTPS for storing web content and pages
Fax Server: Sends and Receives paperless faxes
Application Server: Network Applications
Telephony Server: Call center, Routing calls
Proxy Server: Handles misc tasks in place of of other machines
Hosts:
Any network devices such as workstations and servers that have an IP address.
Client Machine:
Any Device that can ask for access to resources from things like a printer, server, or powerful workstation.


MAN
Metropolitan Area Network: used for large areas such as buildings in cities or connecting different facilities for different purposes.
This normally happens using a carrier provider such as Verizon where they lease a line to your building to provide internet and then can take it away at will.
Smaller concentrated
WAN
Wide Area Network: Span large geographical areas and use some type of router and public links to access. The internet is a WAN!
WAN's can use public and private data transport media/wires such as phone lines to get data across.
WAN's are by definition a internetwork of computers or internet!
Specifically a distributed WAN since devices connect to each other from all around the world.
There is also centralized WAN's where there is a central computer or location where all devices connect.
Centralized WAN Example remote offices around the world connecting to main corporate office.

PAN
Personal Area Networks: Close Proximity Devices connecting such as Bluetooth headphones to the phone which may connected physically to the PC.
CAN
Campus Area Network: limited geographical network such as college campus or corporate campus.
Larger than a LAN but smaller than a MAN and a WAN.
SAN
Storage Area Network: interconnect servers to storage arrays with centralized hard drive and storage media space.
The protocols for a SAN are designed for storage with Fibre Channel being the most common older tech and iSCSI being the newer better protocols.
FCoE (Fibre Channel over Ethernet) is used to encapsulate Fibre Channel into the Ethernet to still use iSCSI technology.
The network Hardware is also different for SANs.
SDWAN
Software Defined Wide Area Network: virtual WAN that uses software to manage devices and services to make changes in the network.
It gets around hardware issues and can dynamically easily handle error management better.
Uses any type of Transport architectures such as MPLS, LTE, and Broad-Band internet serves.
MPLS
Multi-Protocol Label Switching: Super popular WAN protocol which is a switching mechanism that puts labels on data and uses the label to forward the data where it needs to go in a network.
Labeling is done by the routers on the edge of the network
Forwarding is done inside the cloud via MPLS.
Pros: The Physical layout is flexible since it routes through the cloud
Data is the priority
Huge redundancy
one to many logical connections
mGRE
Multi-Point Generic Routing Encapsulation: a protocol given via a service provider that can dynamically terminate and create connections or tunnels to a given node.
A node is like a router which connects to many another devices. The mGRE protocol would allow for just one direct communication to all those devices over one tunnel.
Used in Dynamic Multi-point VPN deployments.


Pear-to-Pear
When the client computers are connected to each other via either a switch or router and they just share each others resources directly to one another.
It on each of the client machines to handle security of its own resources and for them to back up the data on that specific machine since it might be different on the other local machines.
Client-Server
When a server handles all the security and choice of forwarding to where resources are within the network. This includes logging into the client machine.
The server tests your access and then will tell the router where to route you for the actual information such as passwords in the active directory.

Physical vs Logical Typologies
The physical typologies give you the lay of the land and the cables
The Logical typologies are the ones that give you how a digital signal moves around the network.
--- start-multi-column: ID_rcnx
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Bus Topology:
A single line of Ethernet cable in which each device connects to the line via drop cables and some kind of connector.
Drop Cables are the cable that connects the Main wire to the NIC of the Device.
Connector types include T, RJ-45, BNC.
Everyone can see the data on the wire but only the destination device gets the data.
Pros: Easy install, inexpensive.
Cons: Hard to Troubleshoot, change, and move....Fault Tolerance in the main cable is low.
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_xzym
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Star Topology (Hub-and-spoke):
Centralized switch or hub which handles all the connections of each device.
Pros: Fault Tolerant, easily expandable, easy to troublshoot.
Cons: Larger Cost due to more cables, single point of failure due to hub or switch.
Point-to-Point Star Topology & Wireless Access point Topology
These are 2 other advanced versions of the star topology which use another switch to which connects to the other central switch to extend the network for a point-to-point contact.
The Wireless Access Point Topology uses a Access point as its central switching device and is the wireless counter part to the switch/hub.
--- column-break ---


--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_znb5
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Ring Topology:
Each computer is connected to another computer in circle or ring.
Pros: No need for extra network devices such as switch or router.
Cons: Non-fault tolerant, hard to add devices, expensive because of cables, hard to manage.
LAN Vs. WAN use It is almost never used in LAN environments, but is used in WAN for technology such as SONET!
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_0fiq
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Mesh Topology:
It is when every single computer is connected to every other computer. Well every node at least, so mainly the switches are interconnected which are then connected to the computers.
Some nodes have extra wires for even more redundancy.
Partial Mesh Topology: When only some nodes are fully connected and some are left to a lower tolerance. This saves some money and management!
Hybrid Mesh Topology: Some parts are mesh and some are a simper topology which is what is mostly implemented today.
Pros: Max Fault Tolerance
Cons: Super Pricey, hard to manage, increases in difficulty the more computers you have.
--- column-break ---

Important! It is only a full on mesh topology if every singe device is connected to all other devices!
Mathy For n hosts there are this many connections:
--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_fter
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Point-To-Point Topology:
When there is a direct communication between two routers or switches or devices via a physical cable or a logical circuit such as frame relays or MPLS
Routers are linked via a T1 Serial Cable!
Lighting bolts cable represents a WAN link or serial link.
Solid Line cable represents a direct Ethernet link.
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_v98l
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Point-To-Multipoint:
When one device goes to many devices such as one router to many routers.
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_usri
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Hybrid Topology:
When multiple network typologies are used within a network.
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column


Things to note when making the correct selection:
Cost, Ease of Installation, Ease of Maintenance, Fault-Tolerance requirement, Security requirement.
The cost of a large number of quality cables can be more expensive than network devices such as switches or routers.


The strong wired connection of cables behind the switches and that connect all the segments of a network.
Normally uses Gigabit Ethernet to connect to switches and directly to Servers.


The devices that make up a small section of the network that is not the backbone.
The servers may be in one segment. The Devices connected in front of a switch might be another segment.


The boundary between a customers LAN and where the customer connects to the ISP's WAN.
Usually connected to smart jack which is used to run diagnostics on the ISP end, up to the point of your LAN.
The term for the boundary is demarcation point or demarc point which is the line of responsibility for the ISP.


Telephone companies have copper connections to homes to use DSL (Digital Subscriber Lines) which provides internet and was a good alternative to cable or fiber.
Cable companies now offer data and internet services over hybrid fiber/coax on top of there normal cable TV offerings. This uses a modem at the customers house.
There are also Leased Lines which is when a provider installs a direct connection between the provider and customer which is private using copper or fiber.
This provides no sharing of bandwidth and is a secure private connection.


To eliminate the need for external hardware networking devices, you can virtualize the devices onto a server.
Example of this is the vSwitch technology by VMware which makes a virtual network device such as a switch or router.
For the device to do networking functions, it needs a NIC so a vNIC (virtual Network Interface Card) needs to be installed so the virtual device connects to the hypervisor and then from there to the LAN.
This is done via the Hypervisor which allows for multiple VM's to be connected to a single bare metal server at the same time and use its resources.
The process that vSwitch does is called NFV (Network Function virtualization) which is the process of virtualizing the function of different networking devices to run on a single device.

--- start-multi-column: ID_d3vd
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

A model that consists of a Core layer, Distribution layer, and an Access layer which is used to represent the general structure of most networks.
Core Layer:
Backbone of the network where WAN lines are placed to connect the large different area of a network such as across geographical regions.
This layer is high availability and does routing and switching and should be very fast.
Distribution Layer:
This layer is a ton of routing the connections from the core layer to the access layer switches.
This is where packet filtering, security policies, VLAN routing, and defining broadcast domains happens.
Access Layer:
edge switching to host computers.
this is were access to the internet occurs, Quality service(Qos), and power over Ethernet(PoE) and security.
The Collapsed-Core Model is the newer and simpler version of the Three-Tiered Model which just has the Core and Distribution layer as one layer since our modern day switches can handle both functions in one set of devices.
--- column-break ---


--- end-multi-column

--- start-multi-column: ID_78k6
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Copy

Also known as CLOS network, based on the founder Charles Clos.
This network is used exclusively in Data centers with tons of servers.
This network uses a very fast and redundant backbone (spine) which connects to all switches (leaf) which then connect to host servers.
Switches do not connect directly to eachother. They only connect through the spine.
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column


North-South (Vertical):
Southbound traffic is data coming into your internal network from the internet.
Northbound traffic is data going from the internal network to the outside internet.
East-West (Horizontal):
traffic going to and from devices within the network.
data replication, file transfers, inter-process communication.

item.title: Lab 1
item.description:
A LAN is a network typically found in the home or workplace.
A WAN connection connects your home or workplace to the Internet.
A Star topology is also known as hub-and-spoke topology.
The term demarc is used to describe the service-related entry point for a provider.
The Collapsed Core model is used to condense the core and distribution layers into one layer.
A vNIC is a virtualized piece of hardware that connects the virtual machine operating system to the network.
Fibre Channel is typically found inside a Cable or Leased Line(SAN).
The term used to reference the smallest piece of the network is Physical Media(Network Segment).
The MPS? (MPLS) technology uses labels to switch traffic.
The Spine leaf architecture is found in data centers to provide low-latency connectivity to servers.

item.title: The Code Book
item.description:
by Simon Singh

Simple Check list:

Symbols or Alphabet?
Spaces or no spaces?
Letter frequencies!
Di-grams, Tri-grams, and Quad-grams!
Most common One, Two, Three, and Four letter words!
Most common letters to Start and End words!
Most common doubles!
Frequency of letter pairs; Not the same as Di-grams!
Note sometimes the key can be guessed if it uses a phrase!!!
Language Detection How to know if the cipher-text was written in another language?
Check the frequency of the cipher text to see what freq table of which language it lines up with best
Use the frequencies that are the most outliers such as e in English and the last 5 such as z which is below 1% chance!
Note Note: Try and adjust your frequency tables to context about your cipher-text, such as a poem based freq table or a military letter freq table which might skew data.
Links:

Best frequencys
Lots of Digrams and More
Letter Pairs
Get this book! Get Cryptanalysis by Gaines, Helen Fouche for more freq tables!


Add Null characters: alphabet to number 0-99 so the 73 other numbers are randomly added to cipher text. This messes up freq analysis.
Misspell words on purpose to throw off freq analysis.
Use code words in plain text then encrypt them. So “sing” might mean “run”.
Note Note: Deciphering a mono-alphabetic substitution cipher can be really difficult if good techniques are used such as: nulls, miss spellings, and code words are used.


Mono: One or more ciphertext characters correlate to Only one Plaintext character
Poly: One ciphertext character correlates to Many Plaintext character
Ex: Vigenere cipher

Means Same sound, aka many cipher to the same plaintext character.

It is a Mono-Alphabetic substitution cipher which uses multiple cipher texts for one plaintext
Tries to make more options for a char if it has a higher frequency to make all the ciphertext characters be under 1% frequency.
Can still be broke by realizing what characters appear next to other characters such as q and how u always follows q so 3 characters should always follow the char for q IF…..They set up the frequency to be below zero.

item.description:
#writeups/reversing #writeups/BitsCTF #writeups/easy #writeups/2024
#writeups/reversing #writeups/BitsCTF #writeups/easy #writeups/2024

This challenge is a Reversing Challenge and only gave a single file.
--- start-multi-column: ID_kid0
Number of Columns: 1 Largest Column: Large Border: off Copy

--- end-multi-column

As I have said before, If I get a file and I don’t know what it is, I always run the file command on it.
--- start-multi-column: ID_aut9
Number of Columns: 1 Largest Column: Full Border: on Copy

--- end-multi-column

As excepted from reversing challenges, it is a binary aka an executable.
Always try and run it first to see what your goal is:
In Linux in order to make a binary runnable, you must use chmod +x binaryname.
--- start-multi-column: ID_ssez
Number of Columns: 1 Largest Column: Large Copy

--- end-multi-column

Im now thinking, okay I must input some string which will give me the flag, or the string that is inputted is the flag.
Regardless, We should try strings on the binary to see what language this was compiled in or to find the flag possibly. Remember that if there is too many strings use strings -n 10 to limit the output to strings equal to or greater than 10.
--- start-multi-column: ID_xcot
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: Right Border: off Copy

Along side other programing aids, there is a section that says baby-rev.c which shows this is a c program. C programs are reversible using dozens of programs. I like to use this site to quickly size up how hard the challenge is and to see the code de-compiled in different ways.
The website is https://dogbolt.org/:
--- column-break ---
Terminal
--- end-multi-column


The site has many decompilers built in with the most normal to read being the angr decompiler. Here is a list of the compilers:

The way that I solved this was I just skimmed through the code to find where the :P was entered into the console by the program and when I found it I found this section of the code:
--- start-multi-column: ID_uo6b
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Alignment: Center Copy

--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column

So I saw that my :P string is at the top and so I never made it through all the else if statements to make it to the Yippee :3 statement which likely means I entered the correct flag into the program.
Then I realized that each number that is happening in the comparisons are definitely ASCII value.
Originally I Grab each value in order and put it in CyberChef but realized after I had already converted all the values that they are out of order.
This is obvious when you look at the comparisons being made. The second comparisons of the array a0 is a0[4] != 76 . This shows that the values that they are being compared to are out of order.
Just read the ASCII decimal values in order from a0[0] to a0[22]. Put it in CyberChef using from decimal.

Flag BITSCTF{w3lc0me_t0_r3v}CyberChef

item.title: The Challenge
item.description:
#writeups/BroncoCTF #writeups/2024 #writeups/medium #writeups/Stego
#writeups/BroncoCTF #writeups/2024 #writeups/medium #writeups/Stego

--- start-multi-column: ID_hvcz
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

This is a Stego/Forensics Challenge in which you get given a png and a hint that only makes sense in hindsight. Hint: Look inward, and you might find it at the intersection of Mario's color and the number of brothers.
Answer to Hint: Mario Color: Red
Number of Brothers: 2
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column

--- start-multi-column: ID_hqm5
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Here is the png:
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column



I know how to solve this challenge because I read a shitty writeup, and now I understand it and will explain it in a better way to you guys.
Start by always checking an image in online or local steganography tools.
There are too many tools to list all of them so it is up to you to learn them!
AperiSolve & StegOnline are my go-to right now!
Begin by looking through AperiSolve and going through both sites’ checklists. Quote Aperi'Solve is an online platform which performs layer analysis on image. The platform also uses zsteg, steghide, outguess, exiftool, binwalk, foremost and strings for deeper steganography analysis. The platform supports the following images format: .png, .jpg, .gif, .bmp, .jpeg, .jfif, .jpe, .tiff…
--- start-multi-column: ID_qxqb
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: Standard Border: off Alignement: Center Copy


--- column-break ---


--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_8f97
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

When I was looking at these photos when I went to solve the challenge, I was quickly drawn toward SuperImposed(1,3) photo and the Red(1,3) photo because of the obfuscated noisy pixels at the top of the screens.
Attention This is not normal and should be investigated further. If you know your stuff, you will now that each of these photos are outputs of what is called a bit plane.
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column



Every pixel in an image has RGB values.
It looks like a set like this (R, G, B), with each value in the set being a byte or 8 bits long. Example (10100000, 00100000, 11110000): This is the color purple!
--- start-multi-column: ID_z57r
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: right Border: off Copy

An image is just an n by m square of RGB values, representing many pixels.
Each image has 3 different top-level planes, with those being for RGB.
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column

We will deconstruct an image given the information above to understand what a bitplane is.
Each Top-level plane is just a bunch of pixels with 8-bit numbers per pixel.
Take one of the planes now and only take a single bit from each pixel.
Each pixel will now only be a 0 or 1 or black or white.
Now the image is just a black and white image.
This is a bit plane! If you are in the Red top level plane and looking at the LSB(least significant bit)[00000001], that is bit plane R0.
Each top-level plane has 8-bit planes
So, each RGB image has 24-bit planes.
Bit Planes

This idea of showing images in bit planes is the basis for hiding encoded data in an image.
Binary has MSB(most significant bits)[10000000] and LSB. The MSB is most significant because it represents the largest number, so for MSB.
If you encode data in the MSB, you will likely cause noise in the original image, and your stenography will be garbage.
The opposite of this is LSB, where it is only , which is a 1-bit change, so if you encode data into the LSB plane of, let's say, R0, then the original image will not be edited almost at all. This is much harder to see visually.
Even better you can spread your encoded data across The LSB plane for each top-level domain.



As we can see now, There is messed up data in the R2 bit plane. This makes sense now that we know what we are looking at.
Let’s take a look at the other website, StegOnline, which can look at each bit plane individually and will extract files from certain bit planes if you know which plane to extract from.
--- start-multi-column: ID_pks0
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

To confirm, Browsing Bitplane R2 shows us this:
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_z7db
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Let’s try to use their extract tool to extract data from bit plane R2.
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column
--- start-multi-column: ID_3tf8
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

It found a hidden JPG!
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column

--- start-multi-column: ID_6rrq
Number of Columns: 2 Largest Column: standard Border: off Copy

Downloading the jpeg gives an image of Marios and Warios. With 8 of them every single time. This is binary!
Putting the values painfully into CyberChef painfully gives you the flag!
Deep link to Recipe:
Flag bronco{b0ws3r_g0t_th4t_dumpy}
--- column-break ---

--- end-multi-column

Generally, when looking at Crypto ctfs, you will be given 2 things: a program that “encrypts” the flag and the output (which is the encrypted flag). This is what this challenge looked like!

.py is the encryption program and output.txt is the encrypted flag.
The idea is that the encryption program has a flaw in it and can be reversed or exploited. This is what we call bad encryption and finding the vulnerability is the hard part. To do this we must see what the output looks like and understand how the encryption program works.
Using any type of text editor or IDE to open the text file and Python program. I am using Neovim to open and edit the files.

message = open('./message.txt', 'rb').read() + open('./flag.txt', 'rb').read() palette = '.=w-o^*' template = list(open('./mask.txt', 'r').read()) canvas = '' for c in message: for m in [2, 3, 5, 7]: while True: t = template.pop(0) if t == 'X': canvas += palette[c % m] break else: canvas += t print(canvas) Copy
The output.txt file shows us what the encrypted flag looks like but it doesn't tell us what is important, the important information about the output will come from understanding the code. When understanding code you need to comprehend exactly what is going on. So usually you would just trace the code in your head when you are good with python, but for now, I wrote pseudocode to help.
""" This is pseudocode!!!!!! message = text from both messege.txt file and flag.txt file palette = characters used to encode output.txt '.=w-o^*' template = mask used to create the austrailian flag format for output.txt canvas(aka output.txt) = nothing at first for each character in message: for each number in this set [2,3,5,7] loop untill break command t = pull first character from template which should be a X or space value if t equals 'X': add to canvas(output.txt) a value from palette depending on the result of {[c % m]= [(ascii value of character from message) Modulo (value from [2,3,5,7])} break else: add to canvas(output.txt) a space character print(canvas(aka output.txt)) """ Copy
What is going on in the code can be summarized: Each ASCII value for each character in the flag is modulod by the values [2,3,5,7]. Each result will determine which character from the palette(.=w-o^*) is added to the output.txt.
Now, given the pseudocode, I like to make a pseudo input to the output of the code to understand how we can find a vulnerability in this code. To do this we must first understand the output of the mod operator(%). The mod operator simply returns the remainder of the first value divided by the second value. This means that different first values divided by the same second values can return the same result which makes mod(%) not directly reversible. Ex. 5 mod 2 = 1 and 7 mod 2 = 1. If I make an equation like x mod 2 = 1 solve for x……There are an infinite amount of values that make this true. So if I do 27 mod 2 = 1 and only give you the result 1 and tell you I modded with 2, can you find what value I modded? No, you can not. Given this information here is the input-output setup I created.
""" pseudo input to output c1 mod 2 => 0,1 => ., = c1 mod 3 => 0,1,2 => ., =, w c1 mod 5 => 0,1,2,3,4, => ., =, w, -, o c1 mod 7 => 0,1,2,3,4,5,6 => ., =, w, -, o, ^, * . c2 mod 2 . c2 mod 3 . c2 mod 5 . c2 mod 7 . . . . . """ Copy
If this input-output code were to continue to iterate between every character in the flag.txt then it would create the output.txt with every 4 characters from the output.txt representing 1 character in the flag.txt. What about the spaces in the output.txt then? Looking at the if-else statement, you can see that the space added to output.txt is only added when there is a space in the mask, which has nothing to do with the actual “encryption” part. So you have two options: to write the solution to deal with all the spaces when they come along, or to change the output.txt to have no spaces and just read each line in groups of 4. The second option is much simpler.
To change the output.txt to have no spaces or newlines, use this website: “https://www.browserling.com/tools/remove-all-whitespace” or use this command inside of nvim “:%s/\n|\s//g”.

""" ., =, w, -, o, ^, * 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 """ Copy
Based on the input-to-output pseudo code written above, we will have a set of symbols that correlate to the value 0-6 which can be “reverse modulesed” to represent 1 decimal version of an ASCII variable per every 4 chunks of output. If we can reverse just 1 character then we can reverse all of them. Something to note instantly is that ASCII characters only go up to 127 in decimal(https://www.asciitable.com/). So what I said earlier about modulus and having an infinite amount of possibilities that solve the equation x mod 2 = 1 is no longer true. In this instance, we only have 127 values to check which would be very quick for a computer. But even this would still give us many results, we need only 1 solution. But, Again, based on the pseudo-code, each 4 symbols represents 1 character. So the values that satisfied the first equation x mod 2 = ? must also satisfy x mod 3 = ?, x mod 5 = ?, and x mod 7 = ?.
We can begin to see that all we must do is brute force each decimal value from 0-127 and check if it satisfies each modulus equation for every 4 chunks of symbols. This idea works as long as multiple values don’t satisfy all 4 modulus equations. You can try and create a program to solve it from here and it would work. But the actual explanation of why this works and doesn't have any values that have the same outputs is due to something called the Chinese Remainder theorem(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_remainder_theorem).
Here Is the solution I came up with based on the idea we made above:
def find_number_for_conditions(first_digit, second_digit, third_digit, last_digit): num = 0 max_num = 127 # Maximum allowed ASCII value max_iterations = max_num + 1 # Limit the number of iterations while num <= max_num and max_iterations > 0: if ( num % 2 == first_digit and num % 3 == second_digit and num % 5 == third_digit and num % 7 == last_digit ): return num num += 1 max_iterations -= 1 symbol_mapping = {'.': 0, '=': 1, 'w': 2, '-': 3, 'o': 4, '^': 5, '*': 6} input_symbols = "==wo=.=*.w.^==-^..ow==w*.w=o=.w^..--==w*.w=o=...=.=*.w.^==.-.wwo=.=*.w.^.wwo==.-=.=*..--.=-*=....w.^==-^.wwo.w=o.wo*=...==.-.wwo=.o=.wo*==w*..--..--=w=-.w.^==-^= w=-=.-^.wwo..o..wo*=w=-.wwo==oo==w*==.-=www.wwo.wo*==w*==.-.wwo=.w=..-*..-*.wwo.=-o=.oo==.-.wwo==.-=.=*.wwo.wo*=w=-..ow=w=-.wwo==w*..ow=w=-.wwo==.-=.=*==oo=w=-.wwo..ow==w*.w.^.=. w=.=*==oo.wwo=wo.=.=*..ow.=.w==.-.wwo.w=o=.=*.wwo==oo==w*=www=w=-.wwo.w=o.wo*=w=-.wwo==oo=w=-==.-==.-==w*==-^=w=-.wwo..--=.=*.w.^==-^.wwo=w=-.w.^=.=*=.w^==-^.wo*.==o.wwo=wo^=.=*= .w^..ow.wwo..wo..--==w*==-^.wwo=...==.-.=-w.wwo.w-^==.===wo..o..=..=.-o..ow=.=w=.o=..-*.w.^==.-.w=o..ow=.w^=.o=.w=o==o...-*.w.^=w.o..-*..wo=w.o..wo..--.=w-==-^=w.o..wo..ow..-*==o o=w.o..wo..--.=w-==-^=w.o.=w-..ow==.*=w.o.w-.===w=w.o..--..-*..-*=www=.w^.=w.=w.o.w=o.=w-.w-...--=.=w=w.o..-*..ow=w.o=.o=.wo*==o..w.^=.=w==.-=.=w=w.o..ow=.=w==oo.=w-==o..w.^.=.w= .=w..ow==o..w.^==-^=.-.=w.*" input_values = [symbol_mapping[symbol] for symbol in input_symbols] output_values = [] # Iterate through the input values in chunks of 4 for i in range(0, len(input_values), 4): chunk = input_values[i:i+4] if len(chunk) == 4: first_digit, second_digit, third_digit, last_digit = chunk result = find_number_for_conditions(first_digit, second_digit, third_digit, last_digit) output_values.append(result) print("List of output values:", output_values) english_text = ''.join([chr(val) for val in output_values]) print("English text:", english_text) Copy

After running the code above you get this result:
""" Congratulations on solving this challenge! The mask has 900 X's so here are some random words to make the message long enough. Your flag is: DUCTF{r3c0nstruct10n_0f_fl4g_fr0m_fl4g_4r7_by_l00kup_t4bl3_0r_ch1n3s3_r3m41nd3r1ng?} """ Copy

item.title: The Challenge
item.description:
We begin with the challenge description and the downloadable file shown below.

Challenge Description

The first thing that I do when looking at a file with no extension or an extension that I don’t know, I use the file command on it.



When doing this challenge I had already known about .pyc files and how to de-compile them. But you guys may not, so what you should do first is begin researching what a .pyc file is.
Important Using google or chatgpt: you should learn that .pyc is what is created when you run a .py file to make execution of the code faster.
Important The next question should be, can I de-compile this file, since we are in the reverse engineering category. Google or chatgpt will tell you about a few programs that are created to de-compile .pyc files.
Important Ive done the research on the best tools: pydumpck, pycdc/decompyle++, decompyle3, uncompyle6, pydeinstaller(windows), unpyc3, uncompile2, and an online toolhttps://www.lddgo.net/en/string/pyc-compile-decompile).


after decompiling using the online tool which using both pycdc or uncompyle6 we get this:
Important Note: pycdc and uncompyle6 get slightly different results, but both codes run the same.
# Visit https://www.lddgo.net/en/string/pyc-compile-decompile for more information # Python 3.8.0 (3413) class Dill: prefix = 'sun{' suffix = '}' o = [5, 1, 3, 4, 7, 2, 6, 0] def __init__(self) -> None: self.encrypted = 'bGVnbGxpaGVwaWNrdD8Ka2V0ZXRpZGls' def validate(self, value: str) -> bool: return value.startswith(Dill.prefix) and value.endswith(Dill.suffix) or False value = value[len(Dill.prefix):-len(Dill.suffix)] if len(value) != 32: return False c = [value[i:i + 4] for i in range(0, len(value), 4)] value = ''.join([c[i] for i in Dill.o]) if value != self.encrypted: return False return True Copy

Here is the pseudo code for the above code:
""" define varibles show encrypted flag (bGVnbGxpaGVwaWNrdD8Ka2V0ZXRpZGls) validate ctfflag via this function: check for ctf prefix and suffix get rid of prefix and suffix check length for 32 char base64 string c array is set to chucks of 4 of the 32 char string in the order specificed by the varible 'o', rerange the chunks from array 'c' if the new order is = to the encrypted flag then that is the ctf flag. """ Copy

Important Since we know the order that the flag was scrambled in we should be able to easily de-scramble in reverse. Lets split the current encrypted text into the 4 chunks and list there array order which is specified by the variable o .
bGVn bGxp aGVw aWNr dD8K a2V0 ZXRp ZGls
5 1 3 4 7 2 6 0
Important We want to change this to be in the order of 0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7. So lets do that!
0 1 2 3 4 5 5 7
ZGls bGxp a2V0 aGVw aWNr bGVn ZXRp dD8K
Important Remember, based on the code, this is the flag. We can confirm this by running the flag through cyber chefs magic:


So the since the flag format is sun{}. The flag should be sun{``==ZGlsbGxpa2V0aGVwaWNrbGVnZXRpdD8K}==
If you were to run this flag through the checker it would come out as true.

item.title: The Challenge
item.description:
We begin with the challenge description and the downloadable file shown below.


Since we are given a .zip file we will unzip the file.


As usual, if given files with file extensions that you don’t know, you should use the file command.


Let's use the cat command to see what's in the text file to see if it is important.
Important Remember, Reversing challenges are meant to figure out what is going on in the background of a program to then solve the challenge.


This doesn't have any significance to us at the moment, so we can focus on figuring out what is the executable Playdate.


Let's look up what playdate is first: https://play.date/


Okay, so it is a Gameboy-like device. Given some thought, the file we are given is probably for a program that runs on this playdate. Let’s figure out how to open it now:


After reading through either of these links, you will find something called the playdate simulator. You can download the SDK and figure out how to download it after a quick Google search, which runs you through the entire simulator setup, which takes a bit of time.(https://play.date/dev/)
Also, after looking through the docs, you will learn that to open the .pdz file, you have to open the .pdx folder, which includes both the pdxinfo file and the .pdz file.
If you try and open the .pdx folder with playdate, this window of the simulator will pop up:



Many random letters and numbers will pass the screen quickly with a Press a button! Symbol.
The program is limited and not very interesting. Remember, the point of reversing is to find out about what is going on in the background. Let's do more research on this playdate simulator by searching playdate reversing.

Important Boom, we found where we need to go, and hopefully, we will exploit this! Let's look into the GitHub real quick:


The first thing that catches my eye is the [pdz.py](http://pdz.py) file, which will unpack all the files from the container! This is exciting now.
Important Something to note is that this Python script runs using arguments given to the program via the terminal. Without the arguments, you will get an error.


Run python [pdz.py](http://pdz.py) main.pdz ./ or pdz.py main.pdz ./ for windows. This should give you a main.luac file shown below.


After looking up what a .luac file is, you can find on fileinfo.com that it is a compiled version of a lua file. As reversing goes, you have to decompile it.
If we return to GitHub, where we got the pdz program, we can also find a luac decompiler.


Either download the .jar file or unluac.sh. I used the .jar file and ran the command java -jar unluac.jar -o file.lua main.luac.
Finally, this outputs sexy Lua code!!!

Important There is a lot of code, but there are only two essential sections that I will show you: The playdate.update() function and the generateOrder() function.
index = "" lastPressed = "Press a button!" function playdate.update() gfx.clear(gfx.kColorWhite) counter = counter + 1 gfx.drawTextAligned(generateFlag(), 200.0, 120.0, kTextAlignment.center) for i = 1, \#buttons do if playdate.buttonJustPressed(buttons[i]) then pressedButtons = pressedButtons .. i lastPressed = buttons[i] end end gfx.drawTextAligned(lastPressed, 200.0, 160.0, kTextAlignment.center) gfx.drawTextAligned(makeTextDisplayable(pressedButtons), 200.0, 180.0, kTextAlignment.center) gfx.drawTextAligned("Rotate the crank to reset the challenge.", 200.0, 200.0, kTextAlignment.center) if pressedButtons == generateOrder() then print("Pin entered correctly!") gfx.setFont(gfx.font.kVariantBold) cleaned = clean(pressedButtons) print("Flag: sun{" .. cleaned .. "}") gfx.drawTextAligned([[ Flag: sun{]] .. cleaned .. "}", 200.0, 80.0, kTextAlignment.center) end end Copy
function generateOrder() local pinSeed = "" for i = 1, 20 do pinSeed = pinSeed .. i end return pinSeed end Copy
Important Note the generateFlag() function could be cracked because we are given the seed for math.random(). But there is a more straightforward solution.


Based on the playdate.update(), we need our pressedButtons to be equal to the output of the generateOrder() function.
generateOrder() is just the string 1234567891011121314151617181920. So, if we can edit pressedButtons variable to be equal to generateOrder(), then we can win.
Important We can't just press the buttons via the playdate simulator because there are only 6 buttons, which means only 6 possible numbers, and there are 10 numbers needed in this input.

When I was painfully trying to figure out this challenge, I got very good at using the playdate simulator and found all of its features, such as the lua memory tab, lua memory sampler, malloc log, and the debug console. My first thought before realizing that you can edit the pressedButtons variable was to use the debug console to call functions because I had tried this previously, and it worked. With Tim's help, we could edit the variable and get the flag like this.
Run this command pressedButtons = '1234567891011121314151617181920', and this will output into the console: Pin entered correctly! Flag: sun{MIEANBLVFPZJTDOA}

item.title: Way of Thinking
item.description:
The Principle of Abstraction: Simplifying conceptually hard systems or ideas to be understood easier: It's how high schools can learn physics now when back then the books were super complex and confusing.
Abstraction is important but at some point, we have to leave the abstraction world and get more real and complex such as in Physics 3 classes where they include drag and all other forces.
The Principle of Correspondence: Actually taking theory and converting it to the real world: This is the difference between learning ciphers, how they work, their vulnerabilities, and implementing a PKI in a company environment which takes many more skills and is much more difficult.
Given this, when learning at the beginning it is super important to learn abstractly first and then grow into correspondence.
The Principle of Data Type Completeness: I perceive this principle as a guideline to not hyperfocus but to have small baby skills that cover all domains of a given topic. So to not just use one program for a given type of challenge but understand and branch out your skills. Learn the well-known text editors, their history, and the pros and cons. Sure you may focus on using one but knowing them all a little bit can turn out to be super important!


When you are trying to figure out how something works it normally means your missing something and this is the moment you can learn what you truly know what you know and what you don’t know!
This skill takes practice and it is important to embrace this process and use it to add to your Data Type Completeness.

item.title: Commands
item.description:
Unix was created by Ken Thompson and Dennis Ritchie in 1970 at AT&T Bell Lab.
Then GNU Project was made to make a bunch of open source software and tools for a UNIX like operating system. So Richard Stallman made a OS called GNU (Gnu Not Unix) in 1983.
A GNU license was released so that people could create these open source content.
Linux began in 1991 by Linus Torvalds and was combined with the GNU software to add onto the Linux kernel and this created the name GNU/Linux.
Linux is based on Unix and is used as an umbrella term to mean all OS's that are based on Unix.
Linux is used in things like: Websites, car control panels, checkout tills and registers, traffic light controllers.


Commands use -char syntax called flags or switches to do more detailed tasks.
Use --help flag to learn how to use the command tool.
Or use the MAN aka manual page to see the full documentation.
Syntax: man command
cd: Change Directory
cd . (current directory)
cd .. (Previous directory)
ls: List
ls -a (all)
ls -l (long format which lists permissions.)
ls -l fileName (will only do that file)
ls Directory (list the files in that directory)
cat: Concatenate
cat Directory/Path/File.txt (prints out that file)
pwd: Print Working Directory
echo: Print text
echo wowowo (prints the text)
whoami:
find: searches for a file or folder
find -name file (or *.txt)
grep: Comes from the ed editor which had a command called g/re/p which means Global/Regular Expression/Print which finally became its own utility. This searches within files for a specific pattern.
grep "regex pattern" File/Files
wc: Word Count
wc -l File/Files (lines)
wc -w File/Files (words)
wc -c File/Files (Bytes)
wc -m File/Files (characters)
wc -L File/Files (longest line)
touch: create empty file
touch filename

&
- Run Command in the background of your terminal. Copying a large file
Use it to copy a large file that might take awhile to continue using the terminal.
&&
Combine multiple commands into one line. Order is from left to right.
The second command will only run when the first command finishes.
>
- Takes the output of a command and redirects it somewhere else. Creating a new file using echo echo heyyyyyy > welcome
If the file already exists it will overwrite the content.
>>
Will append the content to the bottom of the file instead of overwriting it.


SSH means Secure Shell and is a protocol to execute commands on a remote device that is properly encrypted.
A password is usually needed to connect to a remote device. Command structure ssh username@ipAddress
SCP: Secure Copy Files using SSH protocol to and from remote computer
Makes its own SSH session and so you don't have to be SSH'd into the system already.
scp localFile userName@ipAddress:newFile (Local to Remote)
scp userName@ipAddress:remoteFile localFile (Remote to Local)
Use -r for recursively copy a full directory
Use -P port to specify port (defualt 22)
Use -p to preserve file attributes.
Alternative format: scp localfile site.name.com:newfile
Python3 Webserver: start up a webserver to wget files from a remote machine.
python3 -m http.server
- Default port is 8000 Attention
Without configuration this can be dangerous! There is no authentication.
Secure Alternatives: Caddy, nginx, apache server.
You want to use HTTPS, SSL/TLS certs, and password protected.


Characteristics of a Item are: What actions are allowed and Who can perform the action.
File Ownership
File Permission
Every file has 3 kinds of owners: User, Group, Other
User: owner of the file.
Group: Every user is apart of a group and sometimes the group is called the same as your username.
Use the command groups to see what groups you belong to.
Other: A large group of every single user on the system.
Every file and directory has 3 permissions for each owner:
Files:
Read: view or copy file contents
Write: Modify file content
Execute: run the file if executable
Directories:
Read: list and copy names of all files from a directory
Write: Add or Delete files in a directory
Execute: Can enter the directory Directory RWE Precedence
Directory Execute must be On for Dir Write and all File permissions to work!
If Dir Read and Write are Off, you can still Read and Write to file contents if you know the File names!
Unless you have the sticky bit on "t" for the directory.
Use the stat command to get information about a files permissions or filesystem information.
stat fileName (about file)
stat -f fileName (about filesystem)
Or use the ls -l command for information about the files and folders.

Filetype:
"-": Regular File
"d": Directory
"l": Symbolic Link
File that points to another File, Directory, non-existent files.
Create using: ln -s targetFile linkName
"c": Character Device File
Files that provide access to char oriented devices such as keyboards and mice or serial ports which sequentially handle information. The files provide programs access to these hardware device.
stored in /dev and are associated with device drivers which are shown as numbers when doing ls -l.
"b": Block Device File
Files that provide access to block oriented devices such as storage devices and are stored in /dev.
"p": Named Pipe (FIFO)
(First In First Out), This file acts a intermediate area for processes to inter-communicate between each other. The files are bidirectional and are read and written to.
unnamed or anonymous pipes are use by the | symbol and only exist when the processes are alive.
The named version has persistent storage in the /dev folder.
"s": Unix Domain Socket
Same as named pipe accept it is typically used for communicated between processes across a network or local but similar processes.
Permissions: The read,write, and execute permission for the user, group, and other.

"r": Read
"w": Write
"x": eXecute
"X": Changes only Directories which can be used for large scale chmoding to not change any files!
"-": no Permission
"s": SUID or SGID (Set User or Group ID).
This will make it where when others execute the file it executes it will the User or Group owners permissions.
"S": If the x is not on for user or group to show you that there is an error.
"t": Set sticky bit which makes it so that all files in a given directory can only be deleted or renamed by the file owners or root.
"T": If the x is not on for other to show that there is an error.
Changing Permissions using chmod command:
Two modes: Absolute and Symbolic
Absolute:
Each section(user,group,other) is represented using octal format which is a 7 digit system or 3 bit system.
The MSB or 3rd bit is the "Read" value, 2nd bit is the "Write", and LSB or 1st bit is "eXecute".
This means from binary the "r" value is 4 in decimal, "w" is 2, and "x" is 1, and "-" is 0.
So in total each section will be a number 0 to 7 and make 3 digit number to give to chmod. chmod absolute mode
chmod 356 fileName
User: 3 = 2+1 so Write and eXecute. Or 3 => 011 which is -wx
Group: 5 = 4+1 so Read and eXecute. Or 5 => 101 which is r-x
Other: 6 = 4+2 so Read and Write. Or 6 => 110 which is rw- Special Permissions!
"s" SUID is 4, "s" SGID is 2, and "t" is 1
Use the optional 4th digit to set these values.
chmod 7356 fileName
0777 => drwxrwxrwx
7777 => drwsrwsrwt
7666 => drwSrwSrwT
Symbolic:
Pro of symbolic mode is that you can just change one section of permissions at a time instead of being forced to change them all with absolute mode!
Section Symbols:
"u": user owner
"g": group owner
"o": Other/everyone
"a": all of the above
If no section symbol is used, a is the default!
Operation Symbols:
"+": adding permissions
"-": subtracting permissions
"=": Instead of subtracting or adding, you absolutely set it equal to that permission. (u=r {user=read})
Use the section symbols to pick the owner section, then use operation symbols to give permissions.
- This works for Special Permission too, but they require the section symbols to work. chmod symbolic mode
chmod u+rwx,g-rx,o=xt fileName
Hard Link Count: number of hard links with a default of 1.
User: Owner of file
Group: Group with access to file, Only one group at a time!
Use id -gn userName command to find the Primary group of a user which will be the group on there by default when a user creates a file.
File Size: size in bytes
Modification Time: date time of last modified.
Filename: name of file or folder.


Use the su command which stands for switch user and NOT superuser.
This command is how you can switch to root.
su username (keeps the same shell)
su -l username (logs in as the user and uses there shell and env varibles)
su (will login you into root by default but without its shell)
su - (will login you into root but with its shell and is the same as using -l or --login)

Such as Logs, temp data, backups, and more.

/root
This is the home folder for the root user.
/tmp: Temporary

Processes are units of work on linux and programs have many processes which are managed by the kernel.
They have an ID associated with it called PID (Process ID) which increments in the order at which processes start when the PC turns on.
You can see processes in the /proc directory Note
Processes are different than Jobs!
Jobs are not apart of the OS and use many programs executed as a shell command.
Linux uses namespaces to split up processes into sections which have certain access to resources.
The first process ran when a computer boots up is normally the init system such as (systemd).
Other processes ran afterwards are normally subprocesses of systemd.
ps: (Process Status) Display running processes and other Information
ps aux (all processes included those outside of the terminal and not owned by you)
ps -ux (processes you own and outside your terminal)
ps -U username (processes owned by that user)
ps -C programName (all processes for a given program)
ps -ux | grep regex (use regex to search processes)
Or use: pgrep regex
top: (Table Of Processes)
Use h key to show key binds.
Alternatives: btop, htop
uptime: Tells you how long the computer has been on.
kill: (Uses SIGTERM which terminates the program with cleanup by default)
kill PID (find PID uses pgrep and ps)
kill -[SIG] PID (give a different siginal with the SIG prefix)
Signals: TERM, KILL(Force w/o cleanup), STOP
kill $(pgrep programName)
pkill: (kill all processes for a given program)
pkill programName
xkill: (Interactive kill to choose which foreground process to kill)


systemctl: (List all services and their statuses)
Format: sudo systemctl [option] serviceName
Options: enable, disable, start, stop, restart, reload, status


These are processes that are used to do specific tasks and actions such as running commands, backing up files, running programs, etc at a specific time that repeat over and over again.
Cron is the main process that gets called once a minute.
Cron checks all crontabs which are files in the /var/spool/cron directory
These files have cron jobs in them, one per line.
Blank lines and Commented (#) lines don't get read.
crontab: (command to edit your crontab file)
crontab -e (edit crontab file)
crontab -l (print out crontab file)
crontab -r (delete crontab file)
crontab fileName (make file your crontab file)
sudo crontab -u userName (superuser edits other users crontab files)
Job Syntax: Min Hour DayOfMonth Month DayOfWeek Command
* means the we dont care about that option. Aka it could be any of them.
MIN: {0-59} => (#) or (#-#) Range or (#,#) or (#-#,#-#) or [(*/n) or (#-#/n)] every nth min.
Hour: {0-23} => Same as MIN
DOM: {1-31} => Same as MIN
MONTH: {1-12} => Same as MIN and (jan, feb, mar, ... etc)
DOW: {0(Sun)-6(Sat)} => Same as MIN and (mon, tue, wed, ... etc)
COMMAND: any shell command
Use absolute paths for programs (/usr/bin/cmd) to ensure it works properly
You can use environment variables too! Predefined options
Instead of using the complicated syntax, there are a few predefined options:
@option:
yearly, annually, weekly, daily, midnight, hourly, minutely, secondly
